          "body": "From the indicative of 5:4-5 Paul draws three imperatives in 5:6-8: do not sleep, be alert (*gregoreo*), be sober (*nepho*). Sleep and drunkenness are the night-behaviors of the world; alertness and sobriety are the day-behaviors of believers. Then Paul reaches for armor language (5:8) — the **breastplate of faith and love** and the **helmet of the hope of salvation**. The image draws on Isaiah 59:17 (where Yahweh Himself puts on righteousness as a breastplate and a helmet of salvation) and anticipates Ephesians 6:14-17. The point is that the three theological virtues — faith, love, hope (named together also at 1:3) — are not feelings but defensive equipment. Faith and love guard the vital organs against present pressure; the hope of salvation guards the mind against despair about the future."
