          "title": "Not destined for wrath, but for obtaining salvation through Christ who died for us",
          "body": "Verses 9-10 are the deepest theological ground in the chapter. 'God has not destined us for wrath, but for obtaining salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ' (5:9). The verb *etheto* ('destined, appointed') is the language of divine purpose — God's settled determination. Two destinies are contrasted: wrath (the Day's portion for the unprepared world) and obtaining salvation (the believer's portion through Christ). The means is named with crystal clarity: 'through our Lord Jesus Christ, **who died for us**' (5:10). Five Greek words (*tou apothanontos hyper hemon*) state substitutionary atonement. Then comes a remarkable clause: 'so that whether we are awake or asleep, we will live together with Him.' Here *katheudo* (sleep) is used with a different valence than in 5:6-7 — almost certainly euphemism for physical death (matching 4:13-15). Whether the Day finds us alive or dead, Christ's death secures our life with Him. Reformed commentators read 5:9-10 as a foundational text for divine election to salvation (Calvin, Carson); classical Arminians read *etheto* as God's appointment of the *means and pattern* of salvation rather than individual election. Both readings honor Paul's actual point: the believer's hope rests on God's settled purpose, not the believer's vigilance."
